ra Goodman Salverson, and Akemi Kikumura, and focusing on discourses through which subject positions and identities are produced, the study argues that different concepts of language and translation correspond with particular constructions of subjectivity and attitudes to otherness. A nuanced analysis of intersectional differences reveals gender, race, ethnicity, nationality, culture, and diaspora as unstable categories of representation. ‹/p  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican prose literature -- Minority authors -- History and criticism. 0aAmerican prose literaturexMinority authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAutobiography -- Women authors -- History and criticism. 0aAutobiographyxWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aTranslating and interpreting -- Philosophy. 0aTranslating and interpretingxPhilosophy. 0aWomen immigrants -- Canada -- Biography -- History and criticism. 0aWomen immigrants -- United States -- Biography -- History and criticism. 0aWomen immigrantszCanadaxBiographyxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen immigrantszUnited StatesxBiographyxHistory and criticism. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aLanguage Arts & Disciplines: Translation. 4aLife Writing. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Translating & Interpreting.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012z978311127413308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012z978311127716540uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458399740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554583997423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554583997/original  a978-3-11-127413-3  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-127716-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012b2012  aGBV-deGruyter-alles